{"title_page": "62nd Ohio Infantry", "text_new": "{{Infobox Military Unit\n|unit_name= 62nd Regiment, Ohio Volunteer Infantry\n|image=Flag of Ohio.svg\n|dates= September 17, 1861, to September 1, 1865\n|country= [[United States]]\n|allegiance= [[Union (American Civil War)|Union]]\n|branch= [[Infantry]]\n|equipment= \n<!-- Culture and history -->\n|battles=[[First Battle of Kernstown]]<br/>[[Battle of Winchester (1862)|Battle of Winchester]]<br/>[[Battle of Port Republic]]<br/>[[Seven Days Battles]]<br/>[[Battle of Fort Wagner]]<br/>[[Second Battle of Charleston Harbor|Siege of Charleston]]<br/>[[Battle of Drury's Bluff]]<br/>[[Siege of Petersburg]]<br/>[[Battle of Chaffin's Farm]]<br/>[[Appomattox Campaign]]<br/>[[Battle of Appomattox Court House]]\n}}\n\nThe '''62nd Ohio Volunteer Infantry''' (or '''62nd OVI''') was an [[infantry]] [[regiment]] in the [[Union Army]] during the [[American Civil War]].\n\n==Service==\nThe 62nd Ohio Infantry was organized in [[Zanesville, Ohio|Zanesville]], [[McConnelsville, Ohio|McConnellsville]], and [[Somerton, Ohio]], beginning September 17, 1861, and mustered in for three years service on December 24, 1861, under the command of [[Colonel (United States)|Colonel]] [[Francis Bates Pond]].\n\nThe regiment was attached to 2nd Brigade, [[Frederick W. Lander|Landers]]' Division, [[Army of the Potomac]], to March 1862. 2nd Brigade, [[James Shields (politician, born 1806)|Shields]]' Division, [[Nathaniel P. Banks|Banks]]' [[V Corps (Union Army)|V Corps]], and Department of the Shenandoah, to May 1862. 2nd Brigade, Shields' Division, Department of the Rappahannock, to July 1862. 3rd Brigade, 2nd Division, [[IV Corps (Union Army)|IV Corps]], Army of the Potomac, to September 1862. [[Orris S. Ferry|Ferry's]] Brigade, Division at Suffolk, Virginia, [[VII Corps (Union Army)|VII Corps]], [[Department of Virginia]], to January 1863. 1st Brigade, 3rd Division, [[XVIII Corps (Union Army)|XVIII Corps]], [[Department of North Carolina]], to February 1863. 3rd Brigade, 2nd Division, XVIII Corps, Department of the South, to April 1863. United States forces, [[Folly Island]], South Carolina, [[X Corps (Union Army)|X Corps]], Department of the South, to June 1863. 1st Brigade, Folly Island, South Carolina, X Corps, to July 1863. 1st Brigade, 2nd Division, X Corps, Morris Island, South Carolina, July 1863. 2nd Brigade, [[Morris Island]], South Carolina, X Corps, to October 1863. Howell's Brigade, [[George Henry Gordon|Gordon's]] Division, Folly Island, South Carolina, X Corps, to December 1863. District Hilton Head, South Carolina, X Corps, to April 1864. 1st Brigade, 1st Division, X Corps, [[Army of the James]], Department of Virginia and North Carolina, to December 1864. 1st Brigade, 1st Division, [[XXIV Corps (Union Army)|XXIV Corps]], to September 1865.\n\nThe 62nd Ohio Infantry ceased to exist on September 1, 1865, when it was consolidated with the [[67th Ohio Infantry]].<ref>{{Cite book|title=A compendium of the War of the Rebellion|author=Dyer, Frederick H. |date=1994|publisher=Broadfoot Pub.|oclc=31215782}}</ref>\n\n==Detailed Service==\nThis regiment was organized at Zanesville, McConnellsville and Somerton from Sept. 17 to Dec. 24, 1861, to serve for three years. In Jan., 1862, it went by rail to [[Cumberland, Maryland|Cumberland, Md]]., and there joined the forces under the command of Brig-Gen. Lander, then in camp at [[Patterson Creek|Patterson's Creek]].  After a summer spent in strenuous activity in Virginia, in December it made several reconnaissances from [[Suffolk, Virginia|Suffolk]] to [[Blackwater River (Virginia)|Blackwater]], in one of which a heavy skirmish was had with the enemy. It then went by transports to South Carolina and in the desperate affair at Fort Wagner in July, 1863, it lost 150 men killed, wounded and missing. In January, 1864, it re-enlisted and received the usual 30 days' veteran furlough. During the spring, summer and fall of 1864 it was almost continually under fire not a movement could be made without encountering the enemy. The men of the regiment were compelled to keep an incessant vigil and for weeks at a time dared not throw off their accouterments. In the spring of 1865 the regiment took part in the assault on the Confederate works below [[Petersburg, Virginia|Petersburg]], and on April 2 it was one of the foremost regiments in the assault on [[Fort Gregg]]. It also participated in the action at Appomattox Court House. About Sept. 1, 1865, it was consolidated with the 67th Ohio, and thereafter lost its identity the name of the 67th being retained.<ref>{{Cite book|url=https://archive.org/details/unionarmyhistory02madi|title=The Union army; a history of military affairs in the loyal states, 1861-65 -- records of the regiments in the Union army -- cyclopedia of battles -- memoirs of commanders and soldiers Vol.2|last=|first=|publisher=Federal Publishing Company|year=1908|isbn=|location=Madison, Wis.|pages=}}</ref>\n\n==Casualties==\nThe regiment lost a total of 244 men during service; 11 officers and 102 enlisted men killed or mortally wounded, 2 officers and 129 enlisted men died of disease.\n\n==Commanders==\n* Colonel Francis Bates Pond\n\n==See also==\n{{portal|American Civil War|Ohio}}\n* [[List of Ohio Civil War units]]\n* [[Ohio in the Civil War]]\n\n==References==\n* Dyer, Frederick H. ''A Compendium of the War of the Rebellion'' (Des Moines, IA:  Dyer Pub. Co.), 1908.\n* Ohio Roster Commission. ''Official Roster of the Soldiers of the State of Ohio in the War on the Rebellion, 1861&ndash;1865, Compiled Under the Direction of the Roster Commission'' (Akron, OH: Werner Co.), 1886-1895.\n* Reid, Whitelaw. ''Ohio in the War: Her Statesmen, Her Generals, and Soldiers'' (Cincinnati, OH: Moore, Wilstach, & Baldwin), 1868. {{ISBN|9781154801965}}\n;Attribution\n* {{CWR}}\n\n==External links==\n* [http://www.ohiocivilwar.com/cw62.html Ohio in the Civil War: 62nd Ohio Volunteer Infantry by Larry Stevens]\n* [https://web.archive.org/web/20101229062451/http://ohsweb.ohiohistory.org/exhibits/fftc/relicroom/details.aspx?war=2&flagid=404&unitid=149&warname=Civil%20War Regimental flag of the 62nd Ohio Infantry]\n* [https://web.archive.org/web/20101229062428/http://ohsweb.ohiohistory.org/exhibits/fftc/relicroom/details.aspx?war=2&flagid=74&unitid=149&warname=Civil%20War Regimental flag of the 62nd Ohio Infantry (probably second issue)]\n\n\n\n{{Ohio in the Civil War}}\n\n[[Category:Military units and formations established in 1861]]\n[[Category:Military units and formations disestablished in 1865]]\n[[Category:Ohio Civil War regiments]]\n[[Category:1861 establishments in Ohio]]\n", "text_old": "{{Infobox Military Unit\n|unit_name= 62nd Regiment, Ohio Volunteer Infantry\n|image=Flag of Ohio.svg\n|dates= September 17, 1861, to September 1, 1865\n|country= [[United States]]\n|allegiance= [[Union (American Civil War)|Union]]\n|branch= [[Infantry]]\n|equipment= \n<!-- Culture and history -->\n|battles=[[First Battle of Kernstown]]<br/>[[Battle of Winchester (1862)|Battle of Winchester]]<br/>[[Battle of Port Republic]]<br/>[[Seven Days Battles]]<br/>[[Battle of Fort Wagner]]<br/>[[Second Battle of Charleston Harbor|Siege of Charleston]]<br/>[[Battle of Drury's Bluff]]<br/>[[Siege of Petersburg]]<br/>[[Battle of Chaffin's Farm]]<br/>[[Appomattox Campaign]]<br/>[[Battle of Appomattox Court House]]\n}}\n\nThe '''62nd Ohio Volunteer Infantry''' (or '''62nd OVI''') was an [[infantry]] [[regiment]] in the [[Union Army]] during the [[American Civil War]].\n\n==Service==\nThe 62nd Ohio Infantry was organized in [[Zanesville, Ohio|Zanesville]], [[McConnelsville, Ohio|McConnellsville]], and [[Somerton, Ohio]], beginning September 17, 1861, and mustered in for three years service on December 24, 1861, under the command of [[Colonel (United States)|Colonel]] [[Francis Bates Pond]].\n\nThe regiment was attached to 2nd Brigade, [[Frederick W. Lander|Landers]]' Division, [[Army of the Potomac]], to March 1862. 2nd Brigade, [[James Shields (politician, born 1806)|Shields]]' Division, [[Nathaniel P. Banks|Banks]]' [[V Corps (Union Army)|V Corps]], and Department of the Shenandoah, to May 1862. 2nd Brigade, Shields' Division, Department of the Rappahannock, to July 1862. 3rd Brigade, 2nd Division, [[IV Corps (Union Army)|IV Corps]], Army of the Potomac, to September 1862. [[Orris S. Ferry|Ferry's]] Brigade, Division at Suffolk, Virginia, [[VII Corps (Union Army)|VII Corps]], [[Department of Virginia]], to January 1863. 1st Brigade, 3rd Division, [[XVIII Corps (Union Army)|XVIII Corps]], [[Department of North Carolina]], to February 1863. 3rd Brigade, 2nd Division, XVIII Corps, Department of the South, to April 1863. United States forces, [[Folly Island]], South Carolina, [[X Corps (Union Army)|X Corps]], Department of the South, to June 1863. 1st Brigade, Folly Island, South Carolina, X Corps, to July 1863. 1st Brigade, 2nd Division, X Corps, Morris Island, South Carolina, July 1863. 2nd Brigade, [[Morris Island]], South Carolina, X Corps, to October 1863. Howell's Brigade, [[George Henry Gordon|Gordon's]] Division, Folly Island, South Carolina, X Corps, to December 1863. District Hilton Head, South Carolina, X Corps, to April 1864. 1st Brigade, 1st Division, X Corps, [[Army of the James]], Department of Virginia and North Carolina, to December 1864. 1st Brigade, 1st Division, [[XXIV Corps (Union Army)|XXIV Corps]], to September 1865.\n\nThe 62nd Ohio Infantry ceased to exist on September 1, 1865, when it was consolidated with the [[67th Ohio Infantry]].<ref>{{Cite book|title=A compendium of the War of the Rebellion|author=Dyer, Frederick H. |date=1994|publisher=Broadfoot Pub.|oclc=31215782}}</ref>\n\n==Detailed Service==\nThis regiment was organized at Zanesville, McConnellsville and Somerton from Sept. 17 to Dec. 24, 1861, to serve for three years. In Jan., 1862, it went by rail to [[Cumberland, Maryland|Cumberland, Md]]., and there joined the forces under the command of Brig-Gen. Lander, then in camp at [[Patterson Creek|Patterson's Creek]].  After a summer spent in strenuous activity in Virginia, in December it made several reconnaissances from [[Suffolk, Virginia|Suffolk]] to [[Blackwater River (Virginia)|Blackwater]], in one of which a heavy skirmish was had with the enemy. It then went by transports to South Carolina and in the desperate affair at Fort Wagner in July, 1863, it lost 150 men killed, wounded and missing. In January, 1864, it re-enlisted and received the usual 30 days' veteran furlough. During the spring, summer and fall of 1864 it was almost continually under fire not a movement could be made without encountering the enemy. The men of the regiment were compelled to keep an incessant vigil and for weeks at a time dared not throw off their accouterments. In the spring of 1865 the regiment took part in the assault on the Confederate works below [[Petersburg, Virginia|Petersburg]], and on April 2 it was one of the foremost regiments in the assault on [[Fort Gregg]]. It also participated in the action at Appomattox Court House. About Sept. 1, 1865, it was consolidated with the 67th Ohio, and thereafter lost its identity the name of the 67th being retained.<ref>{{Cite book|url=https://archive.org/details/unionarmyhistory02madi|title=The Union army; a history of military affairs in the loyal states, 1861-65 -- records of the regiments in the Union army -- cyclopedia of battles -- memoirs of commanders and soldiers Vol.2|last=|first=|publisher=Federal Publishing Company|year=1908|isbn=|location=Madison, Wis.|pages=}}</ref>\n\n==Casualties==\nThe regiment lost a total of 244 men during service; 11 officers and 102 enlisted men killed or mortally wounded, 2 officers and 129 enlisted men died of disease.\n\n==Commanders==\n* Colonel Francis Bates Pond\n\n==See also==\n{{portal|American Civil War|Ohio}}\n* [[List of Ohio Civil War units]]\n* [[Ohio in the Civil War]]\n\n==References==\n* Dyer, Frederick H. ''A Compendium of the War of t